00:02:14.030 --> 00:02:15.819
Feel free to embarrass him.

00:02:15.819 --> 00:02:16.610
Don't embarrass me.

00:02:16.610 --> 00:02:18.790
Embarrass this guy.

00:02:18.790 --> 00:02:23.690
So Shawn, my first question
for you a very simple question,

00:02:23.690 --> 00:02:25.165
how do you define happiness?

00:02:27.357 --> 00:02:29.440
SHAWN ACHOR: It's actually
pretty difficult for us

00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:31.770
to define it.

00:02:31.770 --> 00:02:34.860
As Meng mentioned,
I've traveled to now

00:02:34.860 --> 00:02:37.340
over 50 countries over
the past seven years

00:02:37.340 --> 00:02:39.277
studying happiness,
which is great.

00:02:39.277 --> 00:02:41.360
And one of the things that
I realized very quickly

00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:43.470
was that everyone had
a different definition

00:02:43.470 --> 00:02:47.170
of happiness, What they
thought would create happiness,

00:02:47.170 --> 00:02:49.074
the triggers for
happiness seemed

00:02:49.074 --> 00:02:50.990
to be different based
upon different cultures,

00:02:50.990 --> 00:02:53.830
different individuals, even
at the same organization.

00:02:53.830 --> 00:02:56.800
So if you can't define
it, maybe can't study it.

00:02:56.800 --> 00:02:58.345
And if you can't
study it, then we

00:02:58.345 --> 00:03:00.095
can't have things like
positive psychology

00:03:00.095 --> 00:03:02.450
that are looking at how do
we raise levels of happiness

00:03:02.450 --> 00:03:03.810
for other people.

00:03:03.810 --> 00:03:06.114
Part of what we found is
that even though everyone

00:03:06.114 --> 00:03:07.530
in this room and
everyone watching

00:03:07.530 --> 00:03:10.310
has different
definitions of happiness,

00:03:10.310 --> 00:03:12.270
if I ask you on a
scale of 1 to 10

00:03:12.270 --> 00:03:15.340
how happy you felt over the
past two weeks, most of us

00:03:15.340 --> 00:03:17.390
can kind of put ourselves
on that spectrum.

00:03:17.390 --> 00:03:21.615
We can put ourselves
somewhere on that range.

00:03:21.615 --> 00:03:23.840
What we found is that
even though that's

00:03:23.840 --> 00:03:26.550
a subjective experience,
if I go into a hospital

00:03:26.550 --> 00:03:29.220
with a broken arm, there's no
pain meter they can hook me

00:03:29.220 --> 00:03:33.090
up to that automatically means
I'm experiencing an 8 out

00:03:33.090 --> 00:03:36.920
of 10 on a pain scale, the
same thing is true happiness.

00:03:36.920 --> 00:03:38.605
We treat people
based upon the pain

00:03:38.605 --> 00:03:40.750
that they actually experience,
and we can actually

00:03:40.750 --> 00:03:44.000
study people based upon
their subjective experience

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:46.170
of happiness that they're
experiencing in the world.

00:03:46.170 --> 00:03:48.419
Part of what I'm hoping to
do and part of the reason I

00:03:48.419 --> 00:03:51.260
wanted to come to
talk with you is

00:03:51.260 --> 00:03:54.430
that what I'd love for us to do
is to help the world redefine

00:03:54.430 --> 00:03:55.681
what happiness actually means.

00:03:55.681 --> 00:03:57.888
Because I think that there's
a lot of confusion about

00:03:57.888 --> 00:03:59.100
what happiness actually is.

00:03:59.100 --> 00:04:02.130
And if we do come up with a
definition that's aspirational,

00:04:02.130 --> 00:04:04.910
maybe we can start a movement
not only within our schools

00:04:04.910 --> 00:04:08.790
and in our families but in
our companies worldwide.

00:04:08.790 --> 00:04:11.210
There's a lot of articles
that are coming out right now

00:04:11.210 --> 00:04:14.800
talking about how
having a happy life

00:04:14.800 --> 00:04:17.120
and having a meaningful life
that a meaningful life is

00:04:17.120 --> 00:04:19.709
so much better than having
a happy life in terms

00:04:19.709 --> 00:04:23.150
of the levels of health you
experience in the long run.

00:04:23.150 --> 00:04:26.700
I think those studies,
while well-meaning,

00:04:26.700 --> 00:04:28.940
are actually leading us astray.

00:04:28.940 --> 00:04:30.830
Because I think it's
impossible for us

00:04:30.830 --> 00:04:33.400
to sustain happiness
without meaning.

00:04:33.400 --> 00:04:36.282
And as soon as we start to try
to define happiness in our life

00:04:36.282 --> 00:04:38.240
without having meaning,
all we're talking about

00:04:38.240 --> 00:04:39.120
is pleasure.

00:04:39.120 --> 00:04:41.340
And pleasure is very
short-term, right?

00:04:41.340 --> 00:04:43.840
We could put chocolate bars
in front of each of you,

00:04:43.840 --> 00:04:47.179
and then we'd be done in
terms of our happiness.

00:04:47.179 --> 00:04:49.470
Somebody's like, wait, was
that an option this morning?

00:04:49.470 --> 00:04:51.250
I didn't even know that
that would be an option.

00:04:51.250 --> 00:04:51.960
CHADE-MENG TAN: It's Google.

00:04:51.960 --> 00:04:52.730
It's always an option.

00:04:52.730 --> 00:04:53.605
SHAWN ACHOR: Exactly.

00:04:53.605 --> 00:04:54.286
Exactly.

00:04:54.286 --> 00:04:55.910
You've got pleasure
at your fingertips,

00:04:55.910 --> 00:04:58.243
but that doesn't necessarily
mean that you automatically

00:04:58.243 --> 00:04:59.740
have happiness at
your fingertips.

00:04:59.740 --> 00:05:01.690
Because happiness,
the way that we

00:05:01.690 --> 00:05:05.020
are hoping to start your
redefine this for the world

00:05:05.020 --> 00:05:06.990
is to not have
happiness be pleasure,

00:05:06.990 --> 00:05:08.480
because that's very short-term.

00:05:08.480 --> 00:05:09.425
And we get addicted to

00:05:09.425 --> 00:05:09.925
It.

00:05:09.925 --> 00:05:11.591
We were talking about
that this morning.

00:05:11.591 --> 00:05:14.220
If happiness is just a pleasure,
it becomes a trap, right?

00:05:14.220 --> 00:05:16.139
So if I'm not feeling
pleasure right now,

00:05:16.139 --> 00:05:17.430
well, then I must not be happy.

00:05:17.430 --> 00:05:18.790
Then I'm not going to
keep working at this,

00:05:18.790 --> 00:05:20.950
or I'm not going to keep
trying, because this

00:05:20.950 --> 00:05:21.920
is too difficult now.

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:24.830
What I'm interested in is
how do we redefine happiness

00:05:24.830 --> 00:05:31.250
to be-- I stole this definition
from the ancient Greeks--

00:05:31.250 --> 00:05:34.970
the joy that we feel
striving for our potential?

00:05:34.970 --> 00:05:36.620
And I love this definition.

00:05:36.620 --> 00:05:38.650
I was at the Divinity
School before getting

00:05:38.650 --> 00:05:40.295
into studying
positive psychology,

00:05:40.295 --> 00:05:43.130
and I was studying Christian
and Buddhist ethics.

00:05:43.130 --> 00:05:45.250
Because I was interested
in how does the beliefs

00:05:45.250 --> 00:05:47.880
you have about the
world change the actions

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:49.850
you decide to do
within that world.

00:05:49.850 --> 00:05:52.420
And one of the things that I
loved about this definition

00:05:52.420 --> 00:05:55.260
when I saw it is it changes the
way that we pursue happiness.

00:05:55.260 --> 00:05:56.954
Because if happiness
is just pleasure,

00:05:56.954 --> 00:05:58.870
we have to keep running
after it very quickly,

00:05:58.870 --> 00:06:00.970
and we know it's
not going to last.

00:06:00.970 --> 00:06:03.898
But if happiness is
joy, joy is something

00:06:03.898 --> 00:06:05.772
we can feel in the ups
and downs of our life.

00:06:05.772 --> 00:06:08.070
It's something we can experience
even when things are not

00:06:08.070 --> 00:06:10.050
pleasurable, when you're working
on a very difficult project,

00:06:10.050 --> 00:06:11.780
when you're going
for a difficult run,

00:06:11.780 --> 00:06:14.780
or when you're biking into
and it's a really long bike

00:06:14.780 --> 00:06:16.750
ride, whatever is it
you're experiencing.

00:06:16.750 --> 00:06:19.380
Even childbirth is not
a pleasurable experience

00:06:19.380 --> 00:06:21.540
all the time, but
you can actually

00:06:21.540 --> 00:06:23.750
feel joy in the midst of that.

00:06:23.750 --> 00:06:26.330
What I want people to do is
to recognize and to actually

00:06:26.330 --> 00:06:28.850
seek out that joy, which I know
is one of your pet projects

00:06:28.850 --> 00:06:29.670
as well.

00:06:29.670 --> 00:06:33.270
How do you see joy, but joy
that's connected to growth?

00:06:33.270 --> 00:06:36.550
Because if happiness is actually
disconnected from growth,

00:06:36.550 --> 00:06:39.700
it turns out we stagnate
and our happiness

00:06:39.700 --> 00:06:41.150
goes away pretty quickly.

00:06:41.150 --> 00:06:43.580
I love playing video games.

00:06:43.580 --> 00:06:44.580
I love them.

00:06:44.580 --> 00:06:49.040
And they're very high levels of
pleasure, and I'm OK at them.

00:06:49.040 --> 00:06:51.330
But in terms of
long-term meaning,

00:06:51.330 --> 00:06:53.000
there's not too much
for me in my life.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:54.830
Now for some people, there's a
lot of meaning in video games.

00:06:54.830 --> 00:06:56.290
But for me, not so much.

00:06:56.290 --> 00:06:58.540
So if I keep doing it, even
though I'm having pleasure

00:06:58.540 --> 00:07:00.710
that pleasure actually
dissipates after a while,

00:07:00.710 --> 00:07:03.620
because I'm not actually
pursuing any of my potential

00:07:03.620 --> 00:07:05.080
except within that one domain.

00:07:05.080 --> 00:07:07.470
The thing I love about
joy that we experience

00:07:07.470 --> 00:07:09.060
striving towards
our potential is

00:07:09.060 --> 00:07:10.510
that potential
could be anything.

00:07:10.510 --> 00:07:13.900
It could be as an entrepreneur,
as a business leader.

00:07:13.900 --> 00:07:19.200
It could be as a lover,
as a son, as a daughter,

00:07:19.200 --> 00:07:20.340
as a human being.

00:07:20.340 --> 00:07:22.400
And the more than we actually
strive towards that potential,

00:07:22.400 --> 00:07:24.191
that's where people
experience that greater

00:07:24.191 --> 00:07:25.730
levels of happiness,
and it allows

00:07:25.730 --> 00:07:29.150
us to stop making that disjunct
between happiness and success.

00:07:29.150 --> 00:07:32.110
Because I was out in Indonesia,
and I was speaking out

00:07:32.110 --> 00:07:33.362
at one of the factories there.

00:07:33.362 --> 00:07:35.320
And one of the managers
came up to me and said,

00:07:35.320 --> 00:07:37.970
this talk on happiness might
work at places like Google

00:07:37.970 --> 00:07:40.050
or it might work in
places in America,

00:07:40.050 --> 00:07:43.225
but seriously actually our
problem in our country is not

00:07:43.225 --> 00:07:44.460
that people are unhappy work.

00:07:44.460 --> 00:07:47.770
Our problem is sometimes
people are way too happy.

00:07:47.770 --> 00:07:51.460
Because I had this guy come into
work three hours late today,

00:07:51.460 --> 00:07:53.410
and I tried to yell at
him, and he was like,

00:07:53.410 --> 00:07:54.880
what are you doing?

00:07:54.880 --> 00:07:56.630
Let's just relax and
just enjoy ourselves.

00:07:56.630 --> 00:07:59.244
And I was like, that guy
didn't make me happy at all.

00:07:59.244 --> 00:08:01.660
But what he's talking about
there is not happiness, right?

00:08:01.660 --> 00:08:02.790
That's short-term pleasure.

00:08:02.790 --> 00:08:04.320
The guy decide to
stay home that morning

00:08:04.320 --> 00:08:06.653
and didn't do the work that
he was supposed to be doing.

00:08:06.653 --> 00:08:09.099
But if that's what
it is, then long-term

00:08:09.099 --> 00:08:11.390
his levels of happiness are
actually going to decrease.

00:08:11.390 --> 00:08:13.290
He's never going to get to
see what his potential was

00:08:13.290 --> 00:08:14.331
within that organization.

00:08:14.331 --> 00:08:16.390
He might not get to see
what his potential was

00:08:16.390 --> 00:08:20.950
in terms of applying his
self-control and his behavior

00:08:20.950 --> 00:08:21.650
to his task.

00:08:21.650 --> 00:08:23.800
So what we want people
to do is to recognize

00:08:23.800 --> 00:08:30.970
that that can be more
on the side of apathy.

00:08:30.970 --> 00:08:33.860
I think the opposite of
happiness is not unhappiness.

00:08:33.860 --> 00:08:37.280
The opposite of
happiness is apathy,

00:08:37.280 --> 00:08:39.620
which is the loss of joy that
we feel within our lives.

00:08:39.620 --> 00:08:42.049
Because if you think about
it, unhappiness can sometimes

00:08:42.049 --> 00:08:44.190
make us breakup with people
we shouldn't be dating.

00:08:44.190 --> 00:08:46.715
Or unhappiness can cause us
to move to do different jobs,

00:08:46.715 --> 00:08:49.840
or it can cause us to want to
get better grades in school.

00:08:49.840 --> 00:08:51.470
Unhappiness can be very helpful.

00:08:51.470 --> 00:08:53.970
What I think becomes
the problem is

00:08:53.970 --> 00:08:56.260
when we've lost that
joy in our life, when

00:08:56.260 --> 00:08:58.760
we lose that joy striving
towards our potential.

00:08:58.760 --> 00:09:00.850
So I think that there's a
revolution inside of us.

00:09:00.850 --> 00:09:03.285
If we can help people
realize that happiness is joy

00:09:03.285 --> 00:09:05.700
that we feel on the
way to our potential,

00:09:05.700 --> 00:09:07.880
some amazing things
start to change.

00:09:07.880 --> 00:09:09.300
CHADE-MENG TAN: Fascinating.

00:09:09.300 --> 00:09:11.630
It's especially
fascinating in the context

00:09:11.630 --> 00:09:14.870
of one of your teachings
from your previous book,

00:09:14.870 --> 00:09:17.650
which I thought was
ground-breaking.

00:09:17.650 --> 00:09:21.540
And when I first read it,
I was really impressed.

00:09:21.540 --> 00:09:24.230
In your previous book, which
is "The Happiness Advantage,"

00:09:24.230 --> 00:09:27.480
you talk about the relationship
between happiness and success.

00:09:27.480 --> 00:09:30.701
And you put it on
its head, the reverse

00:09:30.701 --> 00:09:32.200
of what everybody
else was thinking.

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:32.470
SHAWN ACHOR: Yeah.

00:09:32.470 --> 00:09:33.080
CHADE-MENG TAN:
Which is everybody

00:09:33.080 --> 00:09:35.810
was thinking that if you're
successful, you're happy,

00:09:35.810 --> 00:09:38.125
which is basically the
premise of Asian parenting.

00:09:38.125 --> 00:09:38.916
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:09:38.916 --> 00:09:39.848
CHADE-MENG TAN: Right?

00:09:39.848 --> 00:09:43.110
Trust me, I know.

00:09:43.110 --> 00:09:45.700
But what you say,
and I agree with you,

00:09:45.700 --> 00:09:47.100
is that it's the reverse.

00:09:47.100 --> 00:09:51.580
It's that happiness
brings about success.

00:09:51.580 --> 00:09:53.500
So can you talk more about that?

00:09:53.500 --> 00:09:54.250
SHAWN ACHOR: Sure.

00:09:54.250 --> 00:09:59.280
So you guys might have heard
"The Battle Hymn of the Tiger

00:09:59.280 --> 00:10:01.950
Mother" book that came out
about tiger parenting, which

00:10:01.950 --> 00:10:04.340
is the style of parenting
you're describing,

00:10:04.340 --> 00:10:07.480
which is I'm going to
push you so far right now,

00:10:07.480 --> 00:10:10.210
and you're going to hate me for
it, but when you're successful,

00:10:10.210 --> 00:10:12.450
when you're off at
Harvard, Stanford,

00:10:12.450 --> 00:10:14.950
when you've got a good job,
then you're going to be happier.

00:10:14.950 --> 00:10:16.060
CHADE-MENG TAN: Right.

00:10:16.060 --> 00:10:18.309
SHAWN ACHOR: And it turns
out that that formula, which

00:10:18.309 --> 00:10:21.330
undergirds our managing styles
at most companies, our learning

00:10:21.330 --> 00:10:23.790
styles, our personal
development styles, it's

00:10:23.790 --> 00:10:27.270
scientifically broken and
backwards for two reasons.

00:10:27.270 --> 00:10:30.804
The first reason is that every
time your brain has a success--

00:10:30.804 --> 00:10:31.970
and you've experienced this.

00:10:31.970 --> 00:10:33.511
Everyone in this
room has experienced

00:10:33.511 --> 00:10:36.690
this-- your brain just
changes the goal post of what

00:10:36.690 --> 00:10:38.765
success looks like for
you almost immediately.

00:10:38.765 --> 00:10:40.140
You've got good
grades in school?

00:10:40.140 --> 00:10:41.620
Don't get excited
yet, because now you

00:10:41.620 --> 00:10:42.953
need to get into better schools.

00:10:42.953 --> 00:10:44.190
You got into a better school?

00:10:44.190 --> 00:10:46.490
Don't get excited there, because
then you have to get a job.

00:10:46.490 --> 00:10:47.510
You don't even have
a job yet, right?

00:10:47.510 --> 00:10:49.060
So you have to get that
internship and job.

00:10:49.060 --> 00:10:50.143
You hit your sales target?

00:10:50.143 --> 00:10:51.600
We raise your sales target.

00:10:51.600 --> 00:10:53.380
You had double growth
earnings last year?

00:10:53.380 --> 00:10:54.140
That's phenomenal.

00:10:54.140 --> 00:10:56.120
That means we can double
the growth again this year.

00:10:56.120 --> 00:10:57.244
And that's not the problem.

00:10:57.244 --> 00:10:59.170
We want to see what your
brain is capable of.

00:10:59.170 --> 00:11:00.650
We want growth to improve.

00:11:00.650 --> 00:11:02.025
We want to see
sales improve, all

00:11:02.025 --> 00:11:03.483
of these different
types of things.

00:11:03.483 --> 00:11:05.920
The problem is where happiness
comes in that formula.

00:11:05.920 --> 00:11:08.080
Because if happiness
comes after success,

00:11:08.080 --> 00:11:09.710
which is a moving
target, the brain

00:11:09.710 --> 00:11:12.590
never gets there for very long.

00:11:12.590 --> 00:11:14.850
We can raise your success
rates your entire life.

00:11:14.850 --> 00:11:15.967
We can raise your income.

00:11:15.967 --> 00:11:17.050
We don't actually do this.

00:11:17.050 --> 00:11:19.190
We watch people whose
success rates rise.

00:11:19.190 --> 00:11:21.080
That'd be very
hard for us to do.

00:11:21.080 --> 00:11:23.330
We watch people whose success
rates rise dramatically,

00:11:23.330 --> 00:11:26.250
and their happiness
levels flatline.

00:11:26.250 --> 00:11:27.490
They actually don't move.

00:11:27.490 --> 00:11:29.775
So as your success
rises in your life,

00:11:29.775 --> 00:11:32.232
your happiness levels will
actually remain about the same.

00:11:32.232 --> 00:11:33.690
But flip around
the formula, if you

00:11:33.690 --> 00:11:36.680
can get people to deepen the
social connection they feel,

00:11:36.680 --> 00:11:38.930
the meaning embedded in the
relationships, the breadth

00:11:38.930 --> 00:11:41.480
and depth of the relationships,
if you change and raise

00:11:41.480 --> 00:11:43.855
their levels of optimism, if
you get people to see stress

00:11:43.855 --> 00:11:45.880
as a challenge instead
of as a threat,

00:11:45.880 --> 00:11:47.710
when our brain is
positive first,

00:11:47.710 --> 00:11:50.870
every single educational
outcome and business outcome

00:11:50.870 --> 00:11:53.580
we can test for
rises dramatically,

00:11:53.580 --> 00:11:54.850
and our success rates rise.

00:11:54.850 --> 00:11:57.200
So raised success rates,
happiness flatlines.

00:11:57.200 --> 00:11:59.790
But raise levels of happiness
withinside organizations

00:11:59.790 --> 00:12:01.360
and schools, and
their success rates

00:12:01.360 --> 00:12:06.060
rise dramatically,
which is phenomenal.

00:12:06.060 --> 00:12:10.134
I spent 12 years at Harvard,
first as an undergraduate

00:12:10.134 --> 00:12:11.550
and then I was at
Divinity School,

00:12:11.550 --> 00:12:13.330
and then I was a
teaching fellow there.

00:12:13.330 --> 00:12:19.290
And when I first got into
Harvard, I applied on a dare,

00:12:19.290 --> 00:12:21.220
so I didn't expect to get in.

00:12:21.220 --> 00:12:22.790
We didn't have any
money for college,

00:12:22.790 --> 00:12:25.640
but I got a Navy
ROTC scholarship,

00:12:25.640 --> 00:12:28.790
which allowed me to
go there through MIT.

00:12:28.790 --> 00:12:31.630
And so I found myself in
classrooms full of people

00:12:31.630 --> 00:12:35.490
who were incredibly smart
and were just amazing.

00:12:35.490 --> 00:12:37.790
And I remember that I could
have felt bad about myself,

00:12:37.790 --> 00:12:40.550
like the mistake, but I remember
just sitting there thinking

00:12:40.550 --> 00:12:42.520
this is amazing to get
to have the opportunity

00:12:42.520 --> 00:12:45.190
like this morning,
to get to spend time

00:12:45.190 --> 00:12:48.370
with all these incredibly
brilliant and motivated people.

00:12:48.370 --> 00:12:51.270
And you can look around,
and for many of you--

00:12:51.270 --> 00:12:55.430
I know some of you are
from Harvard, actually--

00:12:55.430 --> 00:12:57.000
and you could see
the students who

00:12:57.000 --> 00:12:59.630
saw their education
as a privilege.

00:12:59.630 --> 00:13:01.630
They saw what they were
doing as an opportunity,

00:13:01.630 --> 00:13:03.838
and they invested in it in
completely different ways.

00:13:03.838 --> 00:13:05.970
They'd take classes that
they'd get a bad grade in,

00:13:05.970 --> 00:13:08.949
like an A-minus, just
because they wanted to learn.

00:13:08.949 --> 00:13:10.490
Or they'd get involved
with a sport--

00:13:10.490 --> 00:13:12.435
CHADE-MENG TAN:
Obviously not Asian.

00:13:12.435 --> 00:13:13.490
That's like an Asian C.

00:13:13.490 --> 00:13:14.365
SHAWN ACHOR: Exactly.

00:13:14.365 --> 00:13:15.980
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:13:15.980 --> 00:13:18.454
SHAWN ACHOR: I like that.

00:13:18.454 --> 00:13:20.690
CHADE-MENG TAN:
I'm just kidding.

00:13:20.690 --> 00:13:23.184
Almost.

00:13:23.184 --> 00:13:24.600
SHAWN ACHOR: We'd
have people that

00:13:24.600 --> 00:13:27.881
would ride the bench on
a sport for three years

00:13:27.881 --> 00:13:29.630
just so they could
make friends, and those

00:13:29.630 --> 00:13:31.000
are the people who
loved their time there.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:32.010
And actually, in
one of our studies

00:13:32.010 --> 00:13:33.670
we found that those
are the people who

00:13:33.670 --> 00:13:35.200
give the most in
alumni donations

00:13:35.200 --> 00:13:37.150
back to the school
later on, which

00:13:37.150 --> 00:13:40.012
is why Harvard got interested
in happiness in the first place.

00:13:40.012 --> 00:13:42.500
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:13:42.500 --> 00:13:45.530
SHAWN ACHOR: But afterwards,
I got the opportunity

00:13:45.530 --> 00:13:46.390
to stay at Harvard.

00:13:46.390 --> 00:13:49.090
I knew that if I left they
wouldn't let me back in.

00:13:49.090 --> 00:13:51.240
And so I stayed there
for the next eight years,

00:13:51.240 --> 00:13:53.590
and I lived in the dorms with
the freshman as a Proctor

00:13:53.590 --> 00:13:54.730
there.

00:13:54.730 --> 00:14:00.490
And Harvard invited me to do
that-- I wasn't that guy who

00:14:00.490 --> 00:14:02.850
stays in the freshman dorms
meeting people-- for most

00:14:02.850 --> 00:14:03.030
of it.

00:14:03.030 --> 00:14:05.190
So what it meant was I could
watch these students transition

00:14:05.190 --> 00:14:06.522
from high school to college.

00:14:06.522 --> 00:14:08.230
And what I saw very
quickly was no matter

00:14:08.230 --> 00:14:10.852
how happy they were getting into
that school, two weeks later,

00:14:10.852 --> 00:14:12.310
many of them, their
brains were not

00:14:12.310 --> 00:14:14.856
focused on the privilege of
being there or even fully

00:14:14.856 --> 00:14:16.480
focused on their
philosophy or physics.

00:14:16.480 --> 00:14:19.137
Their brains were scattered
thinking about the competition,

00:14:19.137 --> 00:14:21.470
the workload, the stresses,
the hassles, and complaints.

00:14:21.470 --> 00:14:23.920
And very quickly, what was
promised to create great

00:14:23.920 --> 00:14:25.650
happiness wasn't.

00:14:25.650 --> 00:14:28.350
80% of Harvard students,
according to the "Crimson" poll

00:14:28.350 --> 00:14:30.235
that they had, 80%
of them reported

00:14:30.235 --> 00:14:32.610
experiencing depression at
sometime during the four years

00:14:32.610 --> 00:14:33.160
there.

00:14:33.160 --> 00:14:35.770
And a study that came out in
2003 by the University Health

00:14:35.770 --> 00:14:40.000
Services, they measured
6,000 undergraduates

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:43.200
and found that 10% of them
had contemplated suicide

00:14:43.200 --> 00:14:44.810
at some point during
their time there,

00:14:44.810 --> 00:14:46.930
which is extraordinarily high.

00:14:46.930 --> 00:14:48.720
And I know that
these are statistics,

00:14:48.720 --> 00:14:50.187
but those are human beings.

00:14:50.187 --> 00:14:52.520
And it was heartbreaking
watching some of these students

00:14:52.520 --> 00:14:55.070
and some of the
people that we know

00:14:55.070 --> 00:14:59.500
lose that connection to meaning
in their life and the potential

00:14:59.500 --> 00:15:00.727
that they had.

00:15:00.727 --> 00:15:02.560
One of the studies that
I got to do early on

00:15:02.560 --> 00:15:04.590
was I looked at 1,600
Harvard students

00:15:04.590 --> 00:15:07.880
to find out who
rises to the top.

00:15:07.880 --> 00:15:10.100
If you have people that
are extremely intelligent,

00:15:10.100 --> 00:15:12.240
extremely successful,
ambitious, who

00:15:12.240 --> 00:15:14.615
rises to the top in terms of
their happiness and success?

00:15:14.615 --> 00:15:15.739
And I looked at everything.

00:15:15.739 --> 00:15:17.890
I looked at what grades
they got in school.

00:15:17.890 --> 00:15:20.140
I looked at their
familial income.

00:15:20.140 --> 00:15:22.590
We looked at the SAT scores
before getting into school.

00:15:22.590 --> 00:15:24.890
We looked at the number
of friends on Facebook.

00:15:24.890 --> 00:15:26.840
We looked at the number
of romantic partners

00:15:26.840 --> 00:15:27.590
that they had had.

00:15:27.590 --> 00:15:29.180
Which by the way,
at Harvard they've

00:15:29.180 --> 00:15:31.320
dated less than one
person, on average,

00:15:31.320 --> 00:15:33.350
after their entire
four years of college.

00:15:33.350 --> 00:15:33.980
CHADE-MENG TAN:
Must be engineering?

00:15:33.980 --> 00:15:34.522
I don't know.

00:15:34.522 --> 00:15:35.271
SHAWN ACHOR: Yeah.

00:15:35.271 --> 00:15:35.790
Possibly.

00:15:35.790 --> 00:15:39.230
It was lower than any
school we saw so far.

00:15:39.230 --> 00:15:42.395
It was actually 0.5 sexual
partners per Harvard student.

00:15:42.395 --> 00:15:43.770
CHADE-MENG TAN:
Yep, engineering.

00:15:43.770 --> 00:15:44.520
SHAWN ACHOR: Yeah.

00:15:44.520 --> 00:15:45.312
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:15:45.312 --> 00:15:47.561
SHAWN ACHOR: Which I only
mention because I don't even

00:15:47.561 --> 00:15:49.550
know what that
statistic means, 0.5.

00:15:49.550 --> 00:15:51.150
We were always
taught to round up.

00:15:51.150 --> 00:15:52.840
CHADE-MENG TAN: Better than MIT.

00:15:52.840 --> 00:15:54.890
SHAWN ACHOR: Possibly.

00:15:54.890 --> 00:15:55.390
Probably.

00:15:55.390 --> 00:15:57.350
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:15:57.350 --> 00:15:58.920
SHAWN ACHOR: But
0.5 sexual partners,

00:15:58.920 --> 00:16:01.079
it's the scientific
equivalent of second base,

00:16:01.079 --> 00:16:02.620
and it was useless
information to us.

00:16:02.620 --> 00:16:06.340
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:16:06.340 --> 00:16:09.000
SHAWN ACHOR: What we did find
was imagine a student who

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:10.647
ever since they
were one-year-old

00:16:10.647 --> 00:16:12.980
was placed into a crib wearing
a onesie that you can buy

00:16:12.980 --> 00:16:16.410
at the bookstore, at The Coop,
that says "Bound for Harvard"

00:16:16.410 --> 00:16:19.781
and maybe a cute little Yale
hat, in case something terrible

00:16:19.781 --> 00:16:20.280
happened.

00:16:20.280 --> 00:16:23.045
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:16:23.045 --> 00:16:24.420
SHAWN ACHOR: And
ever since there

00:16:24.420 --> 00:16:27.259
were in special pre-K school
that they got into four years

00:16:27.259 --> 00:16:28.800
before they were
conceived, they were

00:16:28.800 --> 00:16:30.390
at the top 1% of their class.

00:16:30.390 --> 00:16:32.960
Junior high, high school,
standardized tests, top 1%.

00:16:32.960 --> 00:16:35.460
They get into Harvard, and they
have a terrible realization.

00:16:35.460 --> 00:16:37.615
50% of them are
now below average.

00:16:37.615 --> 00:16:39.240
And to put it more
poignantly, when

00:16:39.240 --> 00:16:41.280
I was counseling students
I would tell them

00:16:41.280 --> 00:16:44.430
it seems as if 99%
of Harvard students

00:16:44.430 --> 00:16:47.336
do not graduate in
the top 1%, which

00:16:47.336 --> 00:16:48.600
they don't find funny at all.

00:16:48.600 --> 00:16:49.770
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:16:49.770 --> 00:16:51.080
SHAWN ACHOR: But the
reason that's interesting

00:16:51.080 --> 00:16:52.454
is they decide
the only way I can

00:16:52.454 --> 00:16:56.530
be happy is if I'm in the
top 1% of one category of one

00:16:56.530 --> 00:16:57.810
institution, right?

00:16:57.810 --> 00:16:58.394
Not worldwide.

00:16:58.394 --> 00:16:59.851
And they pick
grades-- which if you

00:16:59.851 --> 00:17:02.340
know the research on grades,
you can roll a pair of dice,

00:17:02.340 --> 00:17:05.400
and that's as predictive
of your future job success

00:17:05.400 --> 00:17:07.709
as your college GPA
is, which is why

00:17:07.709 --> 00:17:09.720
a lot of people who make
straight A's in college

00:17:09.720 --> 00:17:13.996
work for people who got
straight C's in business school.

00:17:13.996 --> 00:17:15.079
Some of you are like, yep.

00:17:15.079 --> 00:17:16.787
But part of what I
think is fascinating--

00:17:16.787 --> 00:17:17.710
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:17:17.710 --> 00:17:19.960
SHAWN ACHOR: What I think
is so fascinating about this

00:17:19.960 --> 00:17:22.349
is that we've got the
formula backwards.

00:17:22.349 --> 00:17:25.390
They thought, well, if I
got into a good school,

00:17:25.390 --> 00:17:28.640
if I got a great job, if I
got to where I am in life,

00:17:28.640 --> 00:17:30.120
of course I'd be happier.

00:17:30.120 --> 00:17:32.110
And it turns out that
it doesn't automatically

00:17:32.110 --> 00:17:33.600
cause greater
levels of happiness.

00:17:33.600 --> 00:17:36.711
But amazingly, the formula could
actually work in the other way.

00:17:36.711 --> 00:17:39.210
We found something that we now
call the happiness advantage,

00:17:39.210 --> 00:17:41.207
which is when the brain
is positive it has

00:17:41.207 --> 00:17:43.540
an unfair advantage over the
brain at negative, neutral,

00:17:43.540 --> 00:17:44.380
or stressed.

00:17:44.380 --> 00:17:45.930
You're 31% more productive.

00:17:45.930 --> 00:17:48.380
Sales rise from a
neutral salesperson

00:17:48.380 --> 00:17:51.870
to the same salesperson
at optimistic by 37%.

00:17:51.870 --> 00:17:54.630
We found that people who
provide social support work,

00:17:54.630 --> 00:17:57.000
you're 40% more likely
to receive a promotion

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:58.830
over the next two-year
period of time.

00:17:58.830 --> 00:18:01.330
We find that you live longer.

00:18:01.330 --> 00:18:02.620
We just did a study, actually.

00:18:02.620 --> 00:18:04.221
I love this study.

00:18:04.221 --> 00:18:05.720
I got to work with
one of my friends

00:18:05.720 --> 00:18:09.360
who w one of my students
at Harvard, Alia Crum.

00:18:09.360 --> 00:18:12.750
And she went off to Yale.

00:18:12.750 --> 00:18:15.480
We did a joint study
at UBS in the middle

00:18:15.480 --> 00:18:17.742
of the banking crisis,
the big Swiss bank.

00:18:17.742 --> 00:18:19.450
And one of the things
we were looking for

00:18:19.450 --> 00:18:21.870
is that oftentimes
the companies would

00:18:21.870 --> 00:18:24.670
want to push you very hard, and
then your stress levels rise,

00:18:24.670 --> 00:18:27.516
and then they give you a
stress management program.

00:18:27.516 --> 00:18:28.890
And the stress
management program

00:18:28.890 --> 00:18:30.520
goes something like this.

00:18:30.520 --> 00:18:32.980
Did you know that stress is
related to the 10 leading

00:18:32.980 --> 00:18:35.442
causes of death and disease
in the United States?

00:18:35.442 --> 00:18:37.400
Did you know that the
World Health Organization

00:18:37.400 --> 00:18:39.800
found stress to be
the number one killer?

00:18:39.800 --> 00:18:42.900
Stress is related to 80% to 90%
of all doctor-related visits.

00:18:42.900 --> 00:18:44.900
And stress is catabolic.

00:18:44.900 --> 00:18:47.672
It literally tears down every
organ in the human body.

00:18:47.672 --> 00:18:49.630
As soon as you hear that,
what do you think it?

00:18:49.630 --> 00:18:50.709
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:18:50.709 --> 00:18:51.750
SHAWN ACHOR: More stress.

00:18:51.750 --> 00:18:53.910
You're like, stop
emailing me so much work.

00:18:53.910 --> 00:18:56.820
You're destroying every
organ in my body, which

00:18:56.820 --> 00:18:59.080
I think would make a great
away message at work.

00:18:59.080 --> 00:19:02.640
But part of what we found
is that all of that's true.

00:19:02.640 --> 00:19:04.770
All of that information
is absolutely true.

00:19:04.770 --> 00:19:06.720
Stress is terrible killer.

00:19:06.720 --> 00:19:10.357
But just like with Vitamin
C and coffee and alcohol,

00:19:10.357 --> 00:19:11.940
we keep finding
studies that are like,

00:19:11.940 --> 00:19:14.530
alcohol will save your
life, and it will kill you.

00:19:14.530 --> 00:19:16.440
Vitamin C causes cancer
and cures cancer.

00:19:16.440 --> 00:19:17.510
And we get so frustrated.

00:19:17.510 --> 00:19:18.800
We're like, well, what
am I supposed to do?

00:19:18.800 --> 00:19:20.341
Am I supposed to
drink coffee or not?

00:19:20.341 --> 00:19:22.640
Am I supposed to
drink red wine or not?

00:19:22.640 --> 00:19:25.377
The reason is that it's less
about the external world

00:19:25.377 --> 00:19:26.960
but about how your
body and your brain

00:19:26.960 --> 00:19:30.040
process what comes into your
system and what you experience.

00:19:30.040 --> 00:19:31.570
The same thing's
true with stress.

00:19:31.570 --> 00:19:33.545
So there's an equally
true information

00:19:33.545 --> 00:19:36.990
that says that stress actually
releases a growth hormone that

00:19:36.990 --> 00:19:38.760
speeds up the
recovery of your cells

00:19:38.760 --> 00:19:40.380
faster than anything we've seen.

00:19:40.380 --> 00:19:42.650
Not low levels of stress
but moderate to high

00:19:42.650 --> 00:19:45.040
levels of stress actually
turn on your immune system

00:19:45.040 --> 00:19:46.640
to the highest possible level.

00:19:46.640 --> 00:19:49.520
We found that stress deepens
your social bonds more

00:19:49.520 --> 00:19:52.010
than anything, which is
why last week I was out

00:19:52.010 --> 00:19:54.690
working at the Pentagon, and one
of the things they were saying

00:19:54.690 --> 00:19:57.270
is that's why we on-board
people in the military

00:19:57.270 --> 00:19:59.870
with bootcamp and
not a beach vacation,

00:19:59.870 --> 00:20:02.090
because we know that that
stressful period doesn't

00:20:02.090 --> 00:20:02.992
tear people down.

00:20:02.992 --> 00:20:04.950
It actually causes them
to create these meaning

00:20:04.950 --> 00:20:07.158
structures, these narratives,
and these relationships

00:20:07.158 --> 00:20:09.640
that they talk about for the
entire rest of their life.

00:20:09.640 --> 00:20:11.580
In fact, every moment
of high human potential

00:20:11.580 --> 00:20:14.260
occurs in the midst of
stress, not the absence of it.

00:20:14.260 --> 00:20:16.170
So what we did is we
just showed them videos

00:20:16.170 --> 00:20:18.150
and created a small
training for the UBS

00:20:18.150 --> 00:20:20.520
employees in the middle
of a banking crisis

00:20:20.520 --> 00:20:23.030
when they went through
four restructurings

00:20:23.030 --> 00:20:26.330
and they were told that
they didn't get their bonus.

00:20:26.330 --> 00:20:28.300
One of my very first
talks was actually

00:20:28.300 --> 00:20:30.140
at a Swiss bank out in Zurich.

