But I'm so grateful I did,
because the women in the room

00:30:38.410 --> 00:30:39.310
taught me something.

00:30:39.310 --> 00:30:41.410
They told me that
the experiment still

00:30:41.410 --> 00:30:43.950
worked because they could see
the smile in the other woman's

00:30:43.950 --> 00:30:44.660
eyes.

00:30:44.660 --> 00:30:47.130
And even behind the veil,
the smile was contagious.

00:30:47.130 --> 00:30:49.590
The reason why this is so
fascinating is what we found

00:30:49.590 --> 00:30:53.989
is inside the human brain, what
we discovered also by accident

00:30:53.989 --> 00:30:56.280
is over the past 15 years
we've discovered these things

00:30:56.280 --> 00:30:58.300
in the human brain
called mirror neurons.

00:30:58.300 --> 00:31:00.580
So if you put me into
a fMRI brain scan,

00:31:00.580 --> 00:31:02.889
scan my brain while I'm
smiling, parts of my brain

00:31:02.889 --> 00:31:04.930
will show activation
telling me that I'm smiling.

00:31:04.930 --> 00:31:06.860
But if I stop
smiling, which is what

00:31:06.860 --> 00:31:09.500
you were just trying to do,
and someone smiles at you

00:31:09.500 --> 00:31:11.970
or you see a picture
of somebody smiling,

00:31:11.970 --> 00:31:13.700
those small parts
of your brain called

00:31:13.700 --> 00:31:16.525
mirror neurons will
show activation,

00:31:16.525 --> 00:31:18.740
and they'll tell you you're
the one that's smiling.

00:31:18.740 --> 00:31:23.970
And your motor neurons
will cause your face

00:31:23.970 --> 00:31:26.560
to contort into a smile
before you can stop yourself,

00:31:26.560 --> 00:31:29.597
because you already
think you're smiling.

00:31:29.597 --> 00:31:31.180
So if you were looking
at your partner

00:31:31.180 --> 00:31:32.846
and their lips were
quivering while they

00:31:32.846 --> 00:31:35.330
were trying not to
smile, that's weird.

00:31:35.330 --> 00:31:36.242
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:31:36.242 --> 00:31:37.950
SHAWN ACHOR: That
shouldn't be happening.

00:31:37.950 --> 00:31:40.372
But what's occurring there
is their mirror neurons

00:31:40.372 --> 00:31:42.080
are fighting against
their motor neurons.

00:31:42.080 --> 00:31:43.470
Your brain already
thinks you're smiling,

00:31:43.470 --> 00:31:44.500
so it's like, what's
the problem here,

00:31:44.500 --> 00:31:46.510
face, as your brain
is trying to find out

00:31:46.510 --> 00:31:47.770
what's going on between those.

00:31:47.770 --> 00:31:48.770
These happen with yawns.

00:31:48.770 --> 00:31:51.630
So if you see somebody yawn,
our likelihood of yawning

00:31:51.630 --> 00:31:53.130
increases because
our brain actually

00:31:53.130 --> 00:31:54.450
tells we're the
one that's yawning.

00:31:54.450 --> 00:31:56.170
But why this is so
fascinating and why

00:31:56.170 --> 00:31:58.540
this is crucial to
this contagious effect

00:31:58.540 --> 00:32:01.490
that we can have is it
turns out that if you

00:32:01.490 --> 00:32:05.534
have 15 strangers waiting for
a plane-- they don't even know

00:32:05.534 --> 00:32:06.700
they're part experiment yet.

00:32:06.700 --> 00:32:08.160
They're just at an
airport-- and you

00:32:08.160 --> 00:32:09.630
introduce an
undercover researcher,

00:32:09.630 --> 00:32:12.580
a confederate to stand in
the middle of the 15 people

00:32:12.580 --> 00:32:15.370
and bounce nervously in place,
tap his foot on the floor

00:32:15.370 --> 00:32:18.220
and look at his watch repeatedly
with a frown on his face,

00:32:18.220 --> 00:32:20.740
within two minutes of waiting
for that plane or train,

00:32:20.740 --> 00:32:24.420
depending on the study, 7 to
12 of the 15 individuals will

00:32:24.420 --> 00:32:26.680
unconsciously start
bouncing nervously in place

00:32:26.680 --> 00:32:28.487
and/or tapping their
foot on the ground

00:32:28.487 --> 00:32:30.570
and/or looking at their
watch more than four times

00:32:30.570 --> 00:32:31.220
in two minutes.

00:32:31.220 --> 00:32:32.720
If you don't believe
me, this is one

00:32:32.720 --> 00:32:34.670
of the experiments
you can do yourself

00:32:34.670 --> 00:32:36.606
the next time you
get on a plain,

00:32:36.606 --> 00:32:38.480
if you want to spread
stress and negativity--

00:32:38.480 --> 00:32:39.970
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:32:39.970 --> 00:32:40.820
SHAWN ACHOR: --to the
people on your plane,

00:32:40.820 --> 00:32:42.610
which is why do this
at a different gate.

00:32:42.610 --> 00:32:44.235
But the reason I love
this experiment--

00:32:44.235 --> 00:32:45.050
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:32:45.050 --> 00:32:47.383
SHAWN ACHOR: --is it shows
this, that not only do smiles

00:32:47.383 --> 00:32:49.980
and yawns spread, it turns
out negativity, stress,

00:32:49.980 --> 00:32:53.450
uncertainty, pessimism we can
pick up like secondhand smoke.

00:32:53.450 --> 00:32:54.950
You can be optimistic,
but if you're

00:32:54.950 --> 00:32:56.440
surrounded by people
who are negative,

00:32:56.440 --> 00:32:58.330
your brain through these
mirror neurons can pick it up.

00:32:58.330 --> 00:33:00.400
And when we tell people
that, they're like, OK.

00:33:00.400 --> 00:33:02.050
Well, here are the people
I'm cutting out of my life.

00:33:02.050 --> 00:33:03.841
I'm not going to hang
out with this person.

00:33:03.841 --> 00:33:05.990
I'm going to de-friend
them on Facebook.

00:33:05.990 --> 00:33:09.034
I'm not even going to look
at this person anymore, which

00:33:09.034 --> 00:33:10.700
is awkward because
they're in my family.

00:33:10.700 --> 00:33:13.070
And what happens is in
each one of those moments

00:33:13.070 --> 00:33:14.640
we're eliminating
social connection.

00:33:14.640 --> 00:33:16.540
But these mirror neurons
give us the power

00:33:16.540 --> 00:33:19.307
to actually spread positive
change even better.

00:33:19.307 --> 00:33:20.765
Because as we've
been studying you,

00:33:20.765 --> 00:33:22.240
we've been studying you wrong.

00:33:22.240 --> 00:33:24.330
There's no wires
connecting your brains.

00:33:24.330 --> 00:33:25.589
There's no organic material.

00:33:25.589 --> 00:33:27.130
So we've made the
mistake of assuming

00:33:27.130 --> 00:33:29.965
that all of your brains were
separate, and they're not.

00:33:29.965 --> 00:33:33.020
It misses out on how beautiful
the human organism actually

00:33:33.020 --> 00:33:35.820
is, because our brains
are not wired together.

00:33:35.820 --> 00:33:38.380
Our brains are
wirelessly connected

00:33:38.380 --> 00:33:39.962
through a mirror neuron network.

00:33:39.962 --> 00:33:42.170
Your thoughts right now are
changing your nonverbals,

00:33:42.170 --> 00:33:44.764
how you're sitting here, which
is changing the way that people

00:33:44.764 --> 00:33:46.930
sitting next to you are
processing this information.

00:33:46.930 --> 00:33:49.680
We're in a continual
feedback loop with the people

00:33:49.680 --> 00:33:51.240
that we walk past
in the cafeteria.

00:33:51.240 --> 00:33:53.090
We're in a continual
feedback loop

00:33:53.090 --> 00:33:54.839
with our family members
and our friends.

00:33:54.839 --> 00:33:56.380
And what we found
is if we can buffer

00:33:56.380 --> 00:33:59.420
our brain against the
negative, if we can create even

00:33:59.420 --> 00:34:03.270
a single positive change in
our life, meditation, exercise,

00:34:03.270 --> 00:34:05.010
gratitude, whatever
it is you're doing,

00:34:05.010 --> 00:34:07.050
we can actually watch
that positive effect

00:34:07.050 --> 00:34:09.840
that's occurring in your
brain wirelessly impact

00:34:09.840 --> 00:34:12.630
the people's brains of
the people around you.

00:34:12.630 --> 00:34:14.449
One of the opportunities
I got last year

00:34:14.449 --> 00:34:16.692
was to work at a hospital.

00:34:16.692 --> 00:34:18.150
And hospitals have
a terrible time,

00:34:18.150 --> 00:34:19.733
because when you
think about hospitals

00:34:19.733 --> 00:34:21.639
you think about sickness
and disease, Right?

00:34:21.639 --> 00:34:22.722
And you can't change that.

00:34:22.722 --> 00:34:24.234
But we went into
the Ritz Carlton

00:34:24.234 --> 00:34:25.650
to figure out what
they were doing

00:34:25.650 --> 00:34:27.273
to get people to
love coming there.

00:34:27.273 --> 00:34:28.814
And they have nice
buildings, but one

00:34:28.814 --> 00:34:30.010
of the things that
the train-- maybe you

00:34:30.010 --> 00:34:32.210
know this-- they teach
them to do something

00:34:32.210 --> 00:34:33.719
called the 10-5
Way, which is if you

00:34:33.719 --> 00:34:36.002
walk within 10 feet of
somebody at a Ritz Carlton,

00:34:36.002 --> 00:34:38.210
they're trained to make eye
contact and smile at you.

00:34:38.210 --> 00:34:41.090
And within 5 feet, the employees
are trained to say hello.

00:34:41.090 --> 00:34:42.810
It's actually really
fun to go in and out

00:34:42.810 --> 00:34:45.235
of those sphere with
them at the Ritz,

00:34:45.235 --> 00:34:46.610
even if you're
not staying there.

00:34:46.610 --> 00:34:48.151
But what we love
about the experience

00:34:48.151 --> 00:34:50.400
is that we could import
it down to this hospital,

00:34:50.400 --> 00:34:51.800
to these groups of hospitals.

00:34:51.800 --> 00:34:54.250
And we trained them
post-Katrina down in Louisiana.

00:34:54.250 --> 00:34:56.250
And some of the doctors
were like, why would you

00:34:56.250 --> 00:34:58.370
have to train people to smile?

00:34:58.370 --> 00:34:59.970
Isn't that human nature?

00:34:59.970 --> 00:35:02.820
But then other doctors
were like, uh, you

00:35:02.820 --> 00:35:04.220
hired me to save people's lives.

00:35:04.220 --> 00:35:06.874
It doesn't matter how I
walked down the hallways.

00:35:06.874 --> 00:35:07.790
I save people's lives.

00:35:07.790 --> 00:35:08.470
That's what I'm hired for.

00:35:08.470 --> 00:35:11.230
I'm not going to do this stupid
smiling initiative from HR.

00:35:11.230 --> 00:35:12.370
So we said, that's fine.

00:35:12.370 --> 00:35:14.740
But then we trained
11,000 of their coworkers

00:35:14.740 --> 00:35:17.690
to make eye contact and
smile and to do the 10-5 Way.

00:35:17.690 --> 00:35:20.240
And what happens is
everyone started picking up

00:35:20.240 --> 00:35:22.540
the pattern, the doctors,
and nurses, the staff.

00:35:22.540 --> 00:35:24.320
But the cool part
was the patients,

00:35:24.320 --> 00:35:25.810
who didn't know
what was going on,

00:35:25.810 --> 00:35:28.750
picked up and then started
initiating the social script,

00:35:28.750 --> 00:35:31.710
because they were learning that
when I walk down this hallway

00:35:31.710 --> 00:35:35.755
I'm supposed to treat people
as if they're human beings.

00:35:35.755 --> 00:35:37.380
We pick up social
scripts all the time.

00:35:37.380 --> 00:35:42.080
If you get onto subway in
New York or The T in Boston,

00:35:42.080 --> 00:35:43.690
you start smiling,
some people start

00:35:43.690 --> 00:35:45.020
moving away from you, right?

00:35:45.020 --> 00:35:46.720
Because we know
the social script.

00:35:46.720 --> 00:35:48.380
Let's not necessarily
do eye contact,

00:35:48.380 --> 00:35:50.210
and let's not actually
smile at strangers.

00:35:50.210 --> 00:35:51.910
We know that rule.

00:35:51.910 --> 00:35:54.714
But part of what we
were finding was not

00:35:54.714 --> 00:35:56.130
only did hospital
hallways change,

00:35:56.130 --> 00:35:58.890
which would be a cute story
about how hospitals can change,

00:35:58.890 --> 00:36:00.879
what I was interested
in is what happened

00:36:00.879 --> 00:36:02.670
six months later to
their business outcome.

00:36:02.670 --> 00:36:05.550
Six months later, the
hospitals that did this,

00:36:05.550 --> 00:36:09.890
they saw a significant increase
in their unique patients

00:36:09.890 --> 00:36:11.062
that came to the hospital.

00:36:11.062 --> 00:36:12.520
The likelihood of
patients to refer

00:36:12.520 --> 00:36:15.400
the care, the quality of care
that they received skyrocketed.

00:36:15.400 --> 00:36:17.390
And the doctors'
happiness level at work

00:36:17.390 --> 00:36:19.430
were the highest not only
in the hospital chain

00:36:19.430 --> 00:36:21.800
but in a decade at
that organization.

00:36:21.800 --> 00:36:23.750
That's a one-second
behavioral change

00:36:23.750 --> 00:36:26.620
that shows we can change the
social script around this

00:36:26.620 --> 00:36:29.140
and actually impact not only
our happiness but the quality

00:36:29.140 --> 00:36:31.990
of care that we provide
and our business outcomes.

00:36:31.990 --> 00:36:35.372
My question-- and it's the one
that you have been championing

00:36:35.372 --> 00:36:37.705
here at Google-- is, what if
we had more than one second

00:36:37.705 --> 00:36:38.730
with somebody?

00:36:38.730 --> 00:36:40.940
What if we could change
somebody not just short-term?

00:36:40.940 --> 00:36:43.023
But what if we could
actually change the very lens

00:36:43.023 --> 00:36:44.510
with which we viewed the world?

00:36:44.510 --> 00:36:47.280
And that's where things become
really powerful, I think.

00:36:47.280 --> 00:36:48.450
CHADE-MENG TAN: I have
a suggestion for that--

00:36:48.450 --> 00:36:48.840
SHAWN ACHOR: Yes.

00:36:48.840 --> 00:36:50.330
CHADE-MENG TAN: --wish
is to look at human being

00:36:50.330 --> 00:36:52.500
and to think, I wish for
this person to be happy.

00:36:52.500 --> 00:36:54.580
You don't have to
do or say anything.

00:36:54.580 --> 00:36:55.820
Just think.

00:36:55.820 --> 00:36:59.220
And that thought alone
changes everything.

00:36:59.220 --> 00:37:01.510
Because it changes
your facial expression,

00:37:01.510 --> 00:37:04.750
changes your behavior,
and eventually people,

00:37:04.750 --> 00:37:07.180
they like each other, and
they don't really know why.

00:37:07.180 --> 00:37:08.880
This operates on an
unconscious level.

00:37:08.880 --> 00:37:09.630
SHAWN ACHOR: Yeah.

00:37:09.630 --> 00:37:11.130
CHADE-MENG TAN: So I
suggest that to everybody,

00:37:11.130 --> 00:37:11.840
that one thought.

00:37:11.840 --> 00:37:13.910
I wish for this guy to be happy.

00:37:13.910 --> 00:37:15.260
And then leave it at that.

00:37:15.260 --> 00:37:16.490
See what happens.

00:37:16.490 --> 00:37:17.820
SHAWN ACHOR: That's cool.

00:37:17.820 --> 00:37:20.190
CHADE-MENG TAN: Oh, I love
how you say it's beautiful.

00:37:20.190 --> 00:37:21.600
I see it, and I raise you one--

00:37:21.600 --> 00:37:22.020
SHAWN ACHOR: OK.

00:37:22.020 --> 00:37:22.780
CHADE-MENG TAN:
--which is I think

00:37:22.780 --> 00:37:24.860
that in addition
happiness is contagious.

00:37:24.860 --> 00:37:28.550
The other thing I found to
be contagious is calmness.

00:37:28.550 --> 00:37:32.370
If you walk into a room in
a meditative, calm state,

00:37:32.370 --> 00:37:34.480
no matter how bad things
are, if you walk in

00:37:34.480 --> 00:37:38.080
and sit down meditatively
calm, it starts to spread.

00:37:38.080 --> 00:37:39.840
People start calming down.

00:37:39.840 --> 00:37:41.660
So for those of you
who are meditators,

00:37:41.660 --> 00:37:47.990
practice that in a meeting
where things are not going well.

00:37:47.990 --> 00:37:49.110
Give that a try.

00:37:49.110 --> 00:37:50.750
See if you can change anything.

00:37:50.750 --> 00:37:52.470
And sometimes people notice.

00:37:52.470 --> 00:37:55.836
That guy, every time he walks
in the room, something changes.

00:37:55.836 --> 00:37:56.960
See if that happens to you.

00:37:56.960 --> 00:37:58.001
SHAWN ACHOR: That's cool.

00:37:58.001 --> 00:38:02.040
CHADE-MENG TAN: Which leads
me to the next question.

00:38:02.040 --> 00:38:04.620
The thing I really like
about this book are

00:38:04.620 --> 00:38:07.340
two words that you use,
which I thought was genius.

00:38:07.340 --> 00:38:10.520
And the words you use
are positive genius.

00:38:10.520 --> 00:38:13.920
And can you talk about
what is a positive genius

00:38:13.920 --> 00:38:16.180
and how that relates to
happiness and success?

00:38:16.180 --> 00:38:17.580
SHAWN ACHOR: Sure.

00:38:17.580 --> 00:38:20.870
So only 25% of your
successes here at Google

00:38:20.870 --> 00:38:22.670
are predicted based
upon your intelligence

00:38:22.670 --> 00:38:24.135
and technical skills.

00:38:24.135 --> 00:38:25.690
CHADE-MENG TAN: The rest
is their good looks, right?

00:38:25.690 --> 00:38:27.231
SHAWN ACHOR: The
rest are good looks.

00:38:27.231 --> 00:38:28.280
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:38:28.280 --> 00:38:31.100
SHAWN ACHOR: Which we know from
tech, financials, and medicals,

00:38:31.100 --> 00:38:33.720
where I thought IQ would
matter more, it doesn't.

00:38:33.720 --> 00:38:37.050
About 25% of job success is
predicted by how smart you are.

00:38:37.050 --> 00:38:39.080
75% of your successes
are predicted

00:38:39.080 --> 00:38:41.850
by three other
factors, your optimism,

00:38:41.850 --> 00:38:43.610
the belief that your
behavior matters,

00:38:43.610 --> 00:38:46.710
your social connections, and
the way you perceive stress.

00:38:46.710 --> 00:38:48.710
What we found are that
there's these individuals

00:38:48.710 --> 00:38:51.740
and organizations-- and not
even organizations, nonprofits

00:38:51.740 --> 00:38:56.162
and families-- that we call
positive geniuses, who,

00:38:56.162 --> 00:38:58.620
regardless of the environment
that they find themselves in,

00:38:58.620 --> 00:39:01.810
are able to continually
architect these realities that

00:39:01.810 --> 00:39:04.670
cause them to see past to not
only success but to happiness

00:39:04.670 --> 00:39:06.400
as well.

00:39:06.400 --> 00:39:08.205
Your brains are phenomenal.

00:39:08.205 --> 00:39:09.960
Some of you are like,
yeah, I knew that.

00:39:09.960 --> 00:39:11.050
That's why I work here.

00:39:11.050 --> 00:39:12.780
But your brain can
process about 40 bits

00:39:12.780 --> 00:39:15.170
of information per second,
which is really fast.

00:39:15.170 --> 00:39:17.680
The only problem is your brain
receives 11 million pieces

00:39:17.680 --> 00:39:20.460
of information per second from
all of your nerve endings.

00:39:20.460 --> 00:39:22.670
So as you're constructing
a picture of the world,

00:39:22.670 --> 00:39:26.440
your brain picks and chooses
two to four small facts,

00:39:26.440 --> 00:39:29.010
and then you architect an
entire reality around them.

00:39:29.010 --> 00:39:32.384
And if we know what those
facts are for you, if we

00:39:32.384 --> 00:39:34.800
hear how you're describing
your work or your relationships

00:39:34.800 --> 00:39:37.089
or your life, those facts
you go to immediately,

00:39:37.089 --> 00:39:38.880
those actually predict
not only your levels

00:39:38.880 --> 00:39:40.960
of happiness and
your stress levels

00:39:40.960 --> 00:39:43.610
and how calm you are, but it
predicts your success rates,

00:39:43.610 --> 00:39:46.820
your educational outcomes, your
health outcomes in the future.

00:39:46.820 --> 00:39:49.040
Part of what we found is
that these positive geniuses

00:39:49.040 --> 00:39:52.340
have practiced or have
created these patterns where

00:39:52.340 --> 00:39:55.480
they can continually architect
these positive realities over

00:39:55.480 --> 00:39:56.296
and over again.

00:39:56.296 --> 00:39:57.670
And what I loved
about this is it

00:39:57.670 --> 00:39:59.128
was something that
could be taught.

00:39:59.128 --> 00:40:03.060
I think one of the deepest and
coolest parts of this research

00:40:03.060 --> 00:40:05.270
in positive psychology
is this idea

00:40:05.270 --> 00:40:08.600
that I believe at base is
just that change is possible,

00:40:08.600 --> 00:40:11.840
which I actually think
most people would give

00:40:11.840 --> 00:40:14.125
lip service to but don't
actually believe that.

00:40:14.125 --> 00:40:17.150
Because I think most people
think that just their genes

00:40:17.150 --> 00:40:19.442
are their environment,
that that person's happy

00:40:19.442 --> 00:40:20.650
because they were born happy.

00:40:20.650 --> 00:40:24.550
Or I'm happy because
I was born optimistic

00:40:24.550 --> 00:40:26.285
or my parents were
optimistic, and that's

00:40:26.285 --> 00:40:27.160
the end of the story.

00:40:27.160 --> 00:40:29.910
Or there are some people
that are pessimistic as well.

00:40:29.910 --> 00:40:33.160
There is a researcher up in
Minnesota who's studying twins.

00:40:33.160 --> 00:40:35.280
And they found if you
take identical twins

00:40:35.280 --> 00:40:37.115
and raise them apart--
they were already

00:40:37.115 --> 00:40:38.734
going to be raised apart.

00:40:38.734 --> 00:40:40.150
They didn't do
that for the study,

00:40:40.150 --> 00:40:43.600
but that they have
identical twins raised

00:40:43.600 --> 00:40:46.940
different families, different
environment, same genes,

00:40:46.940 --> 00:40:49.499
and what they found is,
on average, the levels

00:40:49.499 --> 00:40:50.790
of happiness were very similar.

00:40:50.790 --> 00:40:53.570
So he concluded 80% of
your long-term happiness

00:40:53.570 --> 00:40:56.140
is based upon your
genes, which actually I

00:40:56.140 --> 00:40:57.864
believe most people believe.

00:40:57.864 --> 00:40:59.530
They think the majority
of our happiness

00:40:59.530 --> 00:41:03.304
is based upon the way your brain
was wired from the beginning.

00:41:03.304 --> 00:41:04.720
And if you believe
that statement,

00:41:04.720 --> 00:41:06.440
you have to believe
the next one, which

00:41:06.440 --> 00:41:08.310
is his famous statement.

00:41:08.310 --> 00:41:10.660
Stop trying to change
your happiness.

00:41:10.660 --> 00:41:12.530
You're as likely to
change your happiness

00:41:12.530 --> 00:41:14.800
as to change your
height, which is also

00:41:14.800 --> 00:41:16.497
80% determined by genes.

00:41:16.497 --> 00:41:18.830
He's since recanted that
statement, because it turns out

00:41:18.830 --> 00:41:20.580
he was only half right,
which in this case

00:41:20.580 --> 00:41:22.370
makes him fully wrong.

00:41:22.370 --> 00:41:24.865
Because genes do set
the initial baseline.

00:41:27.720 --> 00:41:29.580
We can shine a light
at a three-day-old,

00:41:29.580 --> 00:41:32.372
and if they turn towards that
light and that auditory click,

00:41:32.372 --> 00:41:34.580
they're trying to increase
their neocortical arousal,

00:41:34.580 --> 00:41:37.012
and they're more likely to
be an extrovert at age 10.

00:41:37.012 --> 00:41:38.470
They turn away from
it, and they're

00:41:38.470 --> 00:41:39.922
more likely to be an introvert.

00:41:39.922 --> 00:41:40.630
That's day three.

00:41:40.630 --> 00:41:42.838
We haven't even had time to
screw them up yet, right?

00:41:42.838 --> 00:41:45.070
They've got these
predispositions for this.

00:41:45.070 --> 00:41:46.990
Some of you,
genetically happiness

00:41:46.990 --> 00:41:49.330
is a much easier choice
than it is for other people.

00:41:49.330 --> 00:41:51.970
Same thing with obesity,
with alcoholism,

00:41:51.970 --> 00:41:53.620
all of these different
types of things.

00:41:53.620 --> 00:41:55.750
But that's only the
beginning of the story.

00:41:55.750 --> 00:41:58.940
The reason why we keep finding
genes to be so important

00:41:58.940 --> 00:42:02.977
is that average person
doesn't fight their genes.

00:42:02.977 --> 00:42:05.560
And if you've seen my TED Talk,
one of the things I talk about

00:42:05.560 --> 00:42:07.477
is how most of
our research we're

00:42:07.477 --> 00:42:08.560
interested in the average.

00:42:08.560 --> 00:42:10.851
We want to find out how many
aspirin the average person

00:42:10.851 --> 00:42:12.690
should take if they
get a headache, which

00:42:12.690 --> 00:42:14.023
we should already see a problem.

00:42:14.023 --> 00:42:17.240
Because regardless if you're
90 pounds or 250 pounds, yeah,

00:42:17.240 --> 00:42:19.940
about two pills should do it.

00:42:19.940 --> 00:42:22.090
But as soon as we ask
questions about potential,

00:42:22.090 --> 00:42:24.820
about happiness, about
optimism, about success,

00:42:24.820 --> 00:42:27.352
those are a different
group of questions.

00:42:27.352 --> 00:42:29.310
And when we ask questions
like that, what we do

00:42:29.310 --> 00:42:31.090
is we create a cult
of the average.

00:42:31.090 --> 00:42:33.280
Because if we ask questions
like, how fast can

00:42:33.280 --> 00:42:35.769
a child learn how to
read?-- and in our research,

00:42:35.769 --> 00:42:37.810
we changed it to, how fast
does the average child

00:42:37.810 --> 00:42:40.000
learn how to read, and then
we tailor the classes right

00:42:40.000 --> 00:42:40.874
towards that average.

00:42:40.874 --> 00:42:42.200
Same thing with genes.

00:42:42.200 --> 00:42:45.020
If we look at how much genes
matter, we look at the average,

00:42:45.020 --> 00:42:47.174
and the average
person does not fight

00:42:47.174 --> 00:42:48.590
their genes and
their environment.

00:42:48.590 --> 00:42:51.048
But if you look at those same
graphs with those same twins,

00:42:51.048 --> 00:42:53.680
we find that they can
scatter dramatically

00:42:53.680 --> 00:42:56.500
from their genetic set point
and from our environment.

00:42:56.500 --> 00:42:59.650
Only 10% of your long-term
levels of happiness

00:42:59.650 --> 00:43:01.800
are predicted based
upon the external world.

00:43:01.800 --> 00:43:03.880
90% of your long-term
levels of happiness

00:43:03.880 --> 00:43:07.410
is predicted by how your brain
processes that external world.

00:43:07.410 --> 00:43:09.850
And one of the things we found--
and there might be people

00:43:09.850 --> 00:43:12.380
here in the room, you've
seen a change in your life.

00:43:12.380 --> 00:43:15.472
You've actually seen how you've
become more optimistic or more

00:43:15.472 --> 00:43:17.930
jaded in your life, whatever
direction you've been going on

00:43:17.930 --> 00:43:21.160
that trajectory-- I was
telling you this morning,

00:43:21.160 --> 00:43:24.730
I had an identical twin come
up to me after one of my talks

00:43:24.730 --> 00:43:29.200
and she said, I used to be
a very negative person, just

00:43:29.200 --> 00:43:32.030
like my sister, but now
I'm extremely positive.

00:43:32.030 --> 00:43:33.230
I'm like, that's amazing.

00:43:33.230 --> 00:43:34.310
What did you do?

00:43:34.310 --> 00:43:36.280
How did you break that
cycle from your genes?

00:43:36.280 --> 00:43:37.370
That's what I study.

00:43:37.370 --> 00:43:40.130
And she thought about it,
and she was like, actually,

00:43:40.130 --> 00:43:42.170
I think it happened
when I was 15.

00:43:42.170 --> 00:43:45.960
I was involved in a horrific
car accident, and I almost died.

00:43:45.960 --> 00:43:49.112
And I realized that
life was a privilege

00:43:49.112 --> 00:43:50.820
and that I had a whole
new lease on life.

00:43:50.820 --> 00:43:53.010
And from then on,
I've seen the world

00:43:53.010 --> 00:43:54.360
in a completely different way.

00:43:54.360 --> 00:43:58.620
What I love about that is that's
a trauma that caused growth.

00:43:58.620 --> 00:44:00.420
It wasn't just
post-traumatic stress,

00:44:00.420 --> 00:44:01.690
which is all we hear about.

00:44:01.690 --> 00:44:04.610
But actually, it was trauma
that caused somebody to not only

00:44:04.610 --> 00:44:08.130
grow, create post-traumatic
growth but a deviation

00:44:08.130 --> 00:44:09.010
from our genes.

00:44:09.010 --> 00:44:11.910
And that is what I find that
these positive geniuses are

00:44:11.910 --> 00:44:15.100
able to do is to realize
that they can actually

00:44:15.100 --> 00:44:17.470
be co-creators of the
lens with which they view

00:44:17.470 --> 00:44:19.940
the world with their
environment and their genes,

00:44:19.940 --> 00:44:22.930
so much so we can get people
with genes for pessimism

00:44:22.930 --> 00:44:26.590
to act in the world and to
become high-level optimists.

00:44:26.590 --> 00:44:28.360
We actually haven't
found anyone who

00:44:28.360 --> 00:44:30.316
is not capable of
changing if they're

00:44:30.316 --> 00:44:32.690
willing to be able to make
some of these positive changes

00:44:32.690 --> 00:44:34.414
within their life,
which shows us

00:44:34.414 --> 00:44:36.830
that if we just push against
our environment and our genes

00:44:36.830 --> 00:44:38.790
and create some of
these positive habits

00:44:38.790 --> 00:44:41.549
that you've been doing here
at Google and the programs

00:44:41.549 --> 00:44:43.340
where you get people
to create these ideas,

00:44:43.340 --> 00:44:46.331
if you take advantage of some
of the exercise equipment

00:44:46.331 --> 00:44:48.080
and all of the incredible
things you have,

00:44:48.080 --> 00:44:51.575
you can actually get people to
change from their genetic set

00:44:51.575 --> 00:44:53.996
point and create a whole new
trajectory, which is amazing.

00:44:53.996 --> 00:44:54.870
CHADE-MENG TAN: Yeah.

00:44:54.870 --> 00:44:55.790
Thank you.

00:44:55.790 --> 00:44:58.100
So Alex has the mic.

00:44:58.100 --> 00:45:00.232
Let's get some questions
from the audience.

00:45:00.232 --> 00:45:02.440
Yeah, Alex, you get to choose
who to give the mic to.

00:45:02.440 --> 00:45:03.979
He has the power.

00:45:03.979 --> 00:45:04.520
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:45:04.520 --> 00:45:06.890
A direct follow-up to
what you just said.

00:45:06.890 --> 00:45:10.870
I grew up with the
quote 10% of the world

00:45:10.870 --> 00:45:13.980
is what you make
of it, and 90% is

00:45:13.980 --> 00:45:16.600
how you take it, which is
kind of what you just said.

00:45:16.600 --> 00:45:18.210
You said 90% of
your happiness is

00:45:18.210 --> 00:45:20.902
based on how you process
your external world.

00:45:20.902 --> 00:45:23.694
Do you have some
scientific fact?

00:45:23.694 --> 00:45:25.110
How did you come
up with that 90%?

00:45:25.110 --> 00:45:27.860
Because before I thought
that that was made up.

00:45:27.860 --> 00:45:29.070
SHAWN ACHOR: Yeah.

00:45:29.070 --> 00:45:31.000
That research comes
from a researcher

00:45:31.000 --> 00:45:32.300
named Sonja Lyubomirsky.

00:45:32.300 --> 00:45:34.380
And part of what they
were looking at initially

00:45:34.380 --> 00:45:37.450
was if we know your
external world,

00:45:37.450 --> 00:45:40.240
we can predict short-term
happiness very easily.

00:45:40.240 --> 00:45:42.150
If a stock goes
down, your happiness

00:45:42.150 --> 00:45:43.970
goes down, unless
you short the stock.

00:45:43.970 --> 00:45:47.410
Or if something
bad happens to you,

00:45:47.410 --> 00:45:49.890
immediately you have
a response period.

00:45:49.890 --> 00:45:53.000
If you don't actually have a
response period completely,

00:45:53.000 --> 00:45:56.220
sometimes that can
actually be problematic.

00:45:56.220 --> 00:45:58.790
I don't study people that
are happy all the time,

00:45:58.790 --> 00:46:03.200
because that can actually be a
form of a disorder where they

00:46:03.200 --> 00:46:03.780
don't--

00:46:03.780 --> 00:46:04.940
CHADE-MENG TAN: Or
they live in Colorado.

00:46:04.940 --> 00:46:05.815
SHAWN ACHOR: Exactly.

00:46:05.815 --> 00:46:12.695
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:46:12.695 --> 00:46:14.070
SHAWN ACHOR: So
anyway, what they

00:46:14.070 --> 00:46:22.060
found was your happiness levels
in aggregate over time, which

00:46:22.060 --> 00:46:25.240
is when we watch your
patterns move, only 10% of it

00:46:25.240 --> 00:46:27.670
was predicted by any of
those external factors

00:46:27.670 --> 00:46:28.830
that we were looking for.

00:46:28.830 --> 00:46:30.413
So the rest of it
had to be determined

00:46:30.413 --> 00:46:33.594
based upon your genes and what
she calls the voluntary actions

00:46:33.594 --> 00:46:34.510
you make in your life.

00:46:34.510 --> 00:46:36.962
Those are the habits.

00:46:36.962 --> 00:46:38.420
I like where she's
going with this,

00:46:38.420 --> 00:46:40.386
and it's helpful sometimes
to say those things.

00:46:40.386 --> 00:46:42.510
But I also think we get
stuck with the percentages.

00:46:42.510 --> 00:46:49.914
Because if I'm born with genes
for pessimism-- actually,

00:46:49.914 --> 00:46:51.830
I was born probably with
genes for depression.

00:46:51.830 --> 00:46:54.170
I actually went through two
years of depression myself

00:46:54.170 --> 00:46:57.240
when I was at Harvard while
I was at the Divinity School.

00:46:57.240 --> 00:47:01.280
And as I was coming out of that,
what was helping me pull out

00:47:01.280 --> 00:47:03.679
of it was positive psychology
and some of these habits

00:47:03.679 --> 00:47:04.470
that we were doing.

00:47:04.470 --> 00:47:07.210
I was doing this journaling
exercise where you actually

00:47:07.210 --> 00:47:08.690
journal about
positive experience

00:47:08.690 --> 00:47:10.350
and meaningful
experience over the day.

00:47:10.350 --> 00:47:11.740
And because our
brains can't tell

00:47:11.740 --> 00:47:13.239
the difference
between visualization

00:47:13.239 --> 00:47:16.060
and actual experience,
it doubles the experience

00:47:16.060 --> 00:47:19.500
for the brain, and you
start to see more meaning.

00:47:19.500 --> 00:47:22.434
Even though I have
genes for that,

00:47:22.434 --> 00:47:24.850
I don't actually experience
depression very much any more.

00:47:24.850 --> 00:47:26.920
And when I start to go down
into a trough a little bit,

00:47:26.920 --> 00:47:29.640
I know it's short-lived, and I
can actually pop back out of it

00:47:29.640 --> 00:47:31.020
faster and faster now.

00:47:31.020 --> 00:47:33.130
And if that's the
case, then how much are

00:47:33.130 --> 00:47:35.350
the genes mattering
at this point?

00:47:35.350 --> 00:47:37.610
Are the genes starting
to go from 40% down

00:47:37.610 --> 00:47:40.490
to 30% down to 0%?

00:47:40.490 --> 00:47:42.640
If I have genes for
pessimism but I'm

00:47:42.640 --> 00:47:46.810
acting like an optimist,
maybe they have 0% of effect

00:47:46.810 --> 00:47:47.520
upon people.

00:47:47.520 --> 00:47:50.260
So part of what I think
is just the recognition

00:47:50.260 --> 00:47:52.410
that the external
world does not have

00:47:52.410 --> 00:47:55.320
a tyranny over people's
levels of happiness, which

00:47:55.320 --> 00:47:57.140
is why if you've
traveled a lot you've

00:47:57.140 --> 00:48:01.350
seen-- I've worked with very
wealthy bankers who have just

00:48:01.350 --> 00:48:04.670
been so depressed and devastated
in the middle of a banking

00:48:04.670 --> 00:48:05.400
crisis.

00:48:05.400 --> 00:48:07.350
And I've worked with
farmers in Zimbabwe who

00:48:07.350 --> 00:48:10.290
lost their land who are living
under a military dictator,

00:48:10.290 --> 00:48:12.330
and they're some of the
most optimistic people

00:48:12.330 --> 00:48:13.350
I've ever met.

00:48:13.350 --> 00:48:16.050
So I think it goes
with the common sense

00:48:16.050 --> 00:48:18.580
that we can find people
within every environment that

00:48:18.580 --> 00:48:19.880
are positive and negative.

00:48:19.880 --> 00:48:22.640
I think the key, though,
is how do we view reality.

00:48:22.640 --> 00:48:25.120
Because I was actually
out in northern California

00:48:25.120 --> 00:48:28.170
out here speaking to a
group of software companies,

00:48:28.170 --> 00:48:30.440
all CEOs of these top
software companies.

00:48:30.440 --> 00:48:32.510
You probably know
all these people.

00:48:32.510 --> 00:48:35.060
And one of the CEOs offered
to drive me to the airport

00:48:35.060 --> 00:48:38.442
after my talk, because
he wanted to figure out

00:48:38.442 --> 00:48:40.025
how we could cascade
this research out

00:48:40.025 --> 00:48:41.066
through his organization.

00:48:41.066 --> 00:48:42.690
And so I got into
his really nice car

00:48:42.690 --> 00:48:45.150
and put on my seat belt, and
he got in on the other side

00:48:45.150 --> 00:48:46.510
and immediately started
talking to me about what

00:48:46.510 --> 00:48:48.843
his company was experiencing,
all the change and stress.

00:48:48.843 --> 00:48:50.850
And that bell was
going off in his car

00:48:50.850 --> 00:48:52.433
because he hadn't
put on his seat belt

00:48:52.433 --> 00:48:54.795
yet and just kept going off
and eventually got tired

00:48:54.795 --> 00:48:55.910
and just stopped.

00:48:55.910 --> 00:48:58.436
And I turned to
him and I was like,

00:48:58.436 --> 00:48:59.560
you don't wear a seat belt?

00:48:59.560 --> 00:49:02.100
And he said, no, I
listened to your talk.

00:49:02.100 --> 00:49:03.210
I love your research.

00:49:03.210 --> 00:49:04.280
I'm an optimist.

00:49:04.280 --> 00:49:05.490
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:49:05.490 --> 00:49:08.095
SHAWN ACHOR: I was like,
oh, you're an idiot.

00:49:08.095 --> 00:49:10.439
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:49:10.439 --> 00:49:12.230
SHAWN ACHOR: But I'd
love to work with you.

00:49:12.230 --> 00:49:14.680
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:49:14.680 --> 00:49:17.550
SHAWN ACHOR: Optimism is
great for a lot of things,

00:49:17.550 --> 00:49:19.970
but it doesn't stop
cars from hitting us.

00:49:19.970 --> 00:49:22.390
It doesn't stop reality
from impinging upon us.

00:49:22.390 --> 00:49:24.210
And that's irrational optimism.

00:49:24.210 --> 00:49:25.810
And there's books
and ideas out there

00:49:25.810 --> 00:49:27.510
that if you're like, if
I just change my mindset,

00:49:27.510 --> 00:49:28.870
everything will change for me.

00:49:28.870 --> 00:49:30.700
And that's actually irrational.

00:49:30.700 --> 00:49:33.660
Because if you
sugarcoat the present,

00:49:33.660 --> 00:49:35.700
we make bad decisions
in the future.

00:49:35.700 --> 00:49:38.500
And if we think that
reality won't impact us,

00:49:38.500 --> 00:49:40.560
we don't make any
changes to that reality,

00:49:40.560 --> 00:49:44.290
and it causes us to be blind
to injustices that are going on

00:49:44.290 --> 00:49:47.550
in the world or to racism
or to weaknesses in our life

00:49:47.550 --> 00:49:49.240
that we want to improve.

00:49:49.240 --> 00:49:51.130
Irrational optimists
don't put on a seat belt

00:49:51.130 --> 00:49:52.370
because they don't think
anything bad can happen

00:49:52.370 --> 00:49:54.940
to them, and a pessimist
doesn't put on a seat belt

00:49:54.940 --> 00:49:57.320
because they think they're
going to die anyway.

00:49:57.320 --> 00:50:00.070
But a rational optimist, which
is what I'm hoping people

00:50:00.070 --> 00:50:03.070
go for with this idea,
rational optimism

00:50:03.070 --> 00:50:05.670
doesn't start with
rose-colored glasses.

00:50:05.670 --> 00:50:08.600
It starts with a realistic
assessment of the present, both

00:50:08.600 --> 00:50:11.170
the good and the bad,
but maintains the belief

00:50:11.170 --> 00:50:12.419
that our behavior matters.

00:50:12.419 --> 00:50:14.210
It's linked to our
social support networks.

00:50:14.210 --> 00:50:15.200
I love that.

00:50:15.200 --> 00:50:17.420
The rational optimism takes
a realistic assessment

00:50:17.420 --> 00:50:18.850
of the present
first but maintains

00:50:18.850 --> 00:50:20.240
the belief my behavior matters.

00:50:20.240 --> 00:50:21.790
It's linked to the
people around me.

00:50:21.790 --> 00:50:26.030
And that, I think, is where
we want to go with this.

00:50:26.030 --> 00:50:28.350
I get people after
my talks who say,

00:50:28.350 --> 00:50:30.550
I'm not an optimist
or a pessimist.

00:50:30.550 --> 00:50:33.010
I'm just a realist
right now, which

00:50:33.010 --> 00:50:34.752
usually means
they're a pessimist.

00:50:34.752 --> 00:50:37.980
But what they're saying
is actually nonsensical,

00:50:37.980 --> 00:50:39.990
because both optimists
and pessimists

00:50:39.990 --> 00:50:41.550
can both be realists.

00:50:41.550 --> 00:50:44.360
Realism's seeing the problems
in this world and in our work

00:50:44.360 --> 00:50:45.370
and in our lives.

00:50:45.370 --> 00:50:48.430
Optimism and pessimism is what
happens after the problem.

00:50:48.430 --> 00:50:49.790
So you have to see reality.

00:50:49.790 --> 00:50:51.690
You know that reality
has an impact.

00:50:51.690 --> 00:50:53.700
But do I believe
that that problem is

00:50:53.700 --> 00:50:55.980
permanent and pervasive,
it affects everything,

00:50:55.980 --> 00:50:58.620
or it's local, it's one
part of your reality,

00:50:58.620 --> 00:50:59.700
and that it's temporary?

00:50:59.700 --> 00:51:00.670
This too will pass.

00:51:00.670 --> 00:51:02.810
That's where we want
people to get to,

00:51:02.810 --> 00:51:04.670
not to ignore the
reality but to realize

00:51:04.670 --> 00:51:05.670
that they can change it.

00:51:05.670 --> 00:51:07.360
So I love that quote
that you were talking

00:51:07.360 --> 00:51:09.693
about that you grew up with,
because it really is about,

00:51:09.693 --> 00:51:12.880
how do you take the world that
you have and move forward?

00:51:12.880 --> 00:51:13.520
So thank you.

00:51:13.520 --> 00:51:14.354
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:51:14.354 --> 00:51:16.978
AUDIENCE: I've heard the saying
you are the average of the five

00:51:16.978 --> 00:51:18.562
people you associate
with the most.

00:51:18.562 --> 00:51:19.270
SHAWN ACHOR: Wow.

00:51:19.270 --> 00:51:21.811
AUDIENCE: And whether
it's five or six,

00:51:21.811 --> 00:51:23.560
I don't think the
quantity really matters.

00:51:23.560 --> 00:51:25.370
And the intent of
the question is

00:51:25.370 --> 00:51:27.620
you grow with the
people around you.

00:51:27.620 --> 00:51:32.240
And so I started to really
question my relationships

00:51:32.240 --> 00:51:36.340
from high school to college and
now Google and moving forward.

00:51:36.340 --> 00:51:39.077
Were these relationships
based-- they've changed so much,

00:51:39.077 --> 00:51:40.660
and people that I
used to care about I

00:51:40.660 --> 00:51:42.300
haven't talked to in so long.

00:51:42.300 --> 00:51:44.090
And I'm progressing
forward in my career,

00:51:44.090 --> 00:51:47.567
and I'm really only
associating with people--

00:51:47.567 --> 00:51:49.650
I try to have genuine
conversations with everyone.

00:51:49.650 --> 00:51:51.160
But then I realized
two years later

00:51:51.160 --> 00:51:53.618
that, oh, I don't even talk to
this person I cared about so

00:51:53.618 --> 00:51:56.290
much, just because he's not
a part of my career anymore.

00:51:56.290 --> 00:51:57.620
Because it's such a
huge part in my life.

00:51:57.620 --> 00:51:58.250
SHAWN ACHOR: Yeah.

00:51:58.250 --> 00:51:59.666
AUDIENCE: And so
it's really tough

00:51:59.666 --> 00:52:03.750
to see are all my
relationships that superficial

00:52:03.750 --> 00:52:06.070
to the point of
helping me just kind of

00:52:06.070 --> 00:52:08.964
be a more powerful
force in the world?

00:52:08.964 --> 00:52:11.130
Because I think we all care
about changing the world

00:52:11.130 --> 00:52:13.120
and having an impact,
and that's really hard

00:52:13.120 --> 00:52:14.940
when you try to really
build relationships.

00:52:14.940 --> 00:52:16.550
And when you say cut
people out of your life

00:52:16.550 --> 00:52:17.890
that are bringing
you down, it may

00:52:17.890 --> 00:52:20.181
be that they're in a stage
in which they need the most,

00:52:20.181 --> 00:52:23.260
and you've just cut them out.

00:52:23.260 --> 00:52:26.220
Sometimes I reflect on this,
and I go into a very dark place

00:52:26.220 --> 00:52:26.820
very quickly.

00:52:26.820 --> 00:52:28.640
SHAWN ACHOR: Yeah.

00:52:28.640 --> 00:52:31.050
AUDIENCE: I'm pretty happy
guy, more or less than not.

00:52:31.050 --> 00:52:34.309
But I think about
this stuff a lot,

00:52:34.309 --> 00:52:36.100
and I was wondering
what your opinions are.

00:52:36.100 --> 00:52:37.230
SHAWN ACHOR: Yeah.

00:52:37.230 --> 00:52:39.646
Thank you for sharing that,
because I think about this lot

00:52:39.646 --> 00:52:41.620
too because I find
the same thing.

00:52:41.620 --> 00:52:43.450
It's less about my career.

00:52:43.450 --> 00:52:46.110
It's more about who's in
my immediate vicinity.

00:52:46.110 --> 00:52:48.830
I even saw it with my freshmen
then when I was a Proctor.

00:52:48.830 --> 00:52:51.177
I'd be so close and
tight with my freshmen.

00:52:51.177 --> 00:52:52.760
And then as soon as
they got moved off

00:52:52.760 --> 00:52:55.700
to the River Houses or
the Quad, I was like, OK,

00:52:55.700 --> 00:52:58.172
I've got my new friends,
the new freshmen

00:52:58.172 --> 00:52:59.130
that came in this year.

00:52:59.130 --> 00:53:01.310
And what I found was it was
so frustrating because I cared

00:53:01.310 --> 00:53:03.330
so much about my family
members, these friends

00:53:03.330 --> 00:53:06.400
that I had had in the past, but
they were outside of my sphere,

00:53:06.400 --> 00:53:08.470
because we're so
used to interacting

00:53:08.470 --> 00:53:10.850
with the people that are in
your sphere, which at work,

00:53:10.850 --> 00:53:14.090
if you're focused on work, that
entire sphere might be here.

00:53:14.090 --> 00:53:16.526
So of course the
people closest to you

00:53:16.526 --> 00:53:18.400
might be the people that
are directly related

00:53:18.400 --> 00:53:19.024
to that career.

00:53:22.270 --> 00:53:24.912
And I make a little bit of fun
of cutting the negative people

00:53:24.912 --> 00:53:26.370
out of our life,
because I actually

00:53:26.370 --> 00:53:27.802
don't want people to do that.

00:53:27.802 --> 00:53:30.010
I think it misses out on
how powerful we can actually

00:53:30.010 --> 00:53:32.930
be in these relationships,
even if they're short-term.

00:53:32.930 --> 00:53:35.480
Because at Yale they
found that if you

00:53:35.480 --> 00:53:37.840
have three strangers
come into the room,

00:53:37.840 --> 00:53:39.430
all with different emotions--

00:53:39.430 --> 00:53:41.620
I get asked a lot,
who's more powerful,

00:53:41.620 --> 00:53:44.230
the positive people in your
life and the negative people?

00:53:44.230 --> 00:53:45.270
You might have a positive
team, but there's

00:53:45.270 --> 00:53:47.090
this one negative guy
on the team that's

00:53:47.090 --> 00:53:49.851
dragging the whole team down, or
one positive person that you're

00:53:49.851 --> 00:53:52.350
talking about that's very calm
that gets everyone else to be

00:53:52.350 --> 00:53:53.230
calm.

00:53:53.230 --> 00:53:54.800
We can't answer that question,
because it's different

00:53:54.800 --> 00:53:55.740
every time we test it.

00:53:55.740 --> 00:53:57.030
Sometimes it's the
positive person.

00:53:57.030 --> 00:53:58.488
Sometimes it's the
negative person.

00:53:58.488 --> 00:54:01.550
What we found is it was
a different variable.

00:54:01.550 --> 00:54:03.550
They found that the other
two people in the room

00:54:03.550 --> 00:54:05.640
leave with an increased
likelihood of experiencing

00:54:05.640 --> 00:54:07.800
the emotions of
the most verbally

00:54:07.800 --> 00:54:10.400
and non-verbally expressive
person in the room.

00:54:10.400 --> 00:54:12.420
So what that means is
verbally or non-verbally,

00:54:12.420 --> 00:54:15.690
if I'm very expressive of my
pessimism or my negativity,

00:54:15.690 --> 00:54:18.110
I'm changing that social script.

00:54:18.110 --> 00:54:20.640
And what we found is social
influence in our lives

00:54:20.640 --> 00:54:22.320
is defined by three
things, the strength

00:54:22.320 --> 00:54:25.490
of our message, the immediacy,
how important that message is

00:54:25.490 --> 00:54:27.145
to people, and the
number of sources

00:54:27.145 --> 00:54:29.680
that are giving
that same message.

00:54:29.680 --> 00:54:33.030
What we found is that if you're
wanting to try and create

00:54:33.030 --> 00:54:34.800
a positive effect
upon other people,

00:54:34.800 --> 00:54:37.550
you want to increase the
strength of that message, to be

00:54:37.550 --> 00:54:39.460
more positive verbally
and non-verbally

00:54:39.460 --> 00:54:43.390
in those relationships to try
and change those five or six

00:54:43.390 --> 00:54:45.867
people that might be
in our average circle.

00:54:45.867 --> 00:54:47.700
But also, you're trying
to increase the end.

00:54:47.700 --> 00:54:50.094
Oftentimes when we think
about those negative people,

00:54:50.094 --> 00:54:51.760
we should actually
not be going straight

00:54:51.760 --> 00:54:52.690
for the negative person.

00:54:52.690 --> 00:54:53.925
We should be increasing
the positivity

00:54:53.925 --> 00:54:56.610
of the people in the middle that
we could tip towards positive

00:54:56.610 --> 00:54:58.380
that help make that
person actually

00:54:58.380 --> 00:55:00.092
see a social script
that's more positive.

00:55:00.092 --> 00:55:02.550
But what's interesting, the
other part about your question,

00:55:02.550 --> 00:55:05.610
is these strong ties versus
weak ties, which I actually

00:55:05.610 --> 00:55:07.019
do a lot of research on.

00:55:07.019 --> 00:55:08.810
Weak ties are actually
much more predictive

00:55:08.810 --> 00:55:11.970
of your long-term success
than the strong ties are.

00:55:11.970 --> 00:55:14.910
Happiness levels,
though, are related

00:55:14.910 --> 00:55:17.970
to both, the breadth and
depth of your relationships.

00:55:17.970 --> 00:55:19.930
So part of what
we find is people,

00:55:19.930 --> 00:55:22.300
depending on your introversion
or your extroversion,

00:55:22.300 --> 00:55:25.250
you can have lots of friends or
small friends, deep or broad,

00:55:25.250 --> 00:55:28.720
and what we found is that
it really is how you see it,

00:55:28.720 --> 00:55:31.440
how you see those interactions.

00:55:31.440 --> 00:55:34.459
Do you see them as only
weak ties, in which case

00:55:34.459 --> 00:55:36.250
they don't actually
provide as much meaning

00:55:36.250 --> 00:55:38.150
to you, in which case
you don't actually

00:55:38.150 --> 00:55:40.300
feel sustained by that
social support network?

00:55:40.300 --> 00:55:42.383
It's what we see with
social media a lot of times.

00:55:42.383 --> 00:55:46.910
When people follow people on
Twitter or on any social media

00:55:46.910 --> 00:55:49.150
platform, if they
follow people they

00:55:49.150 --> 00:55:52.410
don't know they get no return
on their investment of time

00:55:52.410 --> 00:55:54.377
in terms of social connection.

00:55:54.377 --> 00:55:55.960
But if they follow
people that they're

00:55:55.960 --> 00:55:57.920
friends from high school
and they see that they just

00:55:57.920 --> 00:56:00.030
had a kid or they just got
a job and they actually

00:56:00.030 --> 00:56:02.940
do see them at some point or
they do interact with them,

00:56:02.940 --> 00:56:04.990
they have a depth of
their social knowledge

00:56:04.990 --> 00:56:07.540
that deepens that relationship
and causes more meaning.

00:56:07.540 --> 00:56:09.869
So what I've been doing in
my life-- this sounds very

00:56:09.869 --> 00:56:11.410
similar to what
you're experiencing--

00:56:11.410 --> 00:56:14.240
is I try to reconnect with
some of those people in very

00:56:14.240 --> 00:56:17.070
short bursts but
in meaningful ways.

00:56:17.070 --> 00:56:19.170
And one of the habits
that I have people

00:56:19.170 --> 00:56:21.210
do at these companies
is every day

00:56:21.210 --> 00:56:23.830
when you get into work write
a two-minute email praising

00:56:23.830 --> 00:56:26.190
or thanking or reconnecting
with one person.

00:56:26.190 --> 00:56:26.690
That's it.

00:56:26.690 --> 00:56:28.760
Two minutes maximum,
so it's super short.

00:56:28.760 --> 00:56:31.160
It's two or three sentences.

00:56:31.160 --> 00:56:31.709
Try it today.

00:56:31.709 --> 00:56:33.250
Just connect with
one of those people

00:56:33.250 --> 00:56:36.075
you feel like is outside
of that career sphere.

00:56:36.075 --> 00:56:37.700
And if you do it for
three days, you'll

00:56:37.700 --> 00:56:39.280
literally become addicted
to it, because you're

00:56:39.280 --> 00:56:41.696
going to spend all day long
thinking about how amazing you

00:56:41.696 --> 00:56:43.446
were for writing that email.

00:56:43.446 --> 00:56:45.300
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:56:45.300 --> 00:56:47.780
SHAWN ACHOR: But what happens
is 21 days later as you've

00:56:47.780 --> 00:56:50.030
reconnected to those people,
your brain realizes, wow,

00:56:50.030 --> 00:56:52.530
I have incredibly
robust social support.

00:56:52.530 --> 00:56:56.410
I saw some of you this morning
that I hadn't seen from my time

00:56:56.410 --> 00:56:57.860
at Harvard, and
it's so exciting.

00:56:57.860 --> 00:57:00.670
I haven't seen you in so
long, and it's so exciting

00:57:00.670 --> 00:57:02.850
to have those opportunities.

00:57:02.850 --> 00:57:05.210
What we found is social
support is the greatest

00:57:05.210 --> 00:57:07.410
predictor of long-term
happiness we have.

00:57:07.410 --> 00:57:11.080
So instead of
fleeing from negative

00:57:11.080 --> 00:57:14.800
or only investing in our sphere,
if we can find just small ways

00:57:14.800 --> 00:57:18.022
to increase and deepen
that social connection,

00:57:18.022 --> 00:57:20.230
we've found it's the greatest
predictor of happiness.

00:57:20.230 --> 00:57:21.605
At Columbia, they
found that if I

00:57:21.605 --> 00:57:24.532
know the collective IQ on a team
and the years of experience,

00:57:24.532 --> 00:57:26.240
neither of those are
as predictive as how

00:57:26.240 --> 00:57:28.690
tight the team feels, so
we know it's important.

00:57:28.690 --> 00:57:31.330
But then the last part, my
favorite statistic right now,

00:57:31.330 --> 00:57:34.720
which is actually by a guy
named Dr. House, which I think

00:57:34.720 --> 00:57:39.160
is hilarious, he found
that the social connection

00:57:39.160 --> 00:57:43.040
is as predictive of how long
you will live as obesity,

00:57:43.040 --> 00:57:45.760
high blood pressure, or smoking.

00:57:45.760 --> 00:57:47.570
We fight so hard
against the negative,

00:57:47.570 --> 00:57:50.270
and we forget about how
powerful two minutes

00:57:50.270 --> 00:57:52.180
of a positive
interaction could be.

00:57:52.180 --> 00:57:54.310
So yeah, I feel the
exact same thing,

00:57:54.310 --> 00:57:56.840
and I think it's how we
perceive those relationships

00:57:56.840 --> 00:57:58.781
that, while they
might be temporary,

00:57:58.781 --> 00:58:01.030
that doesn't take away the
meaning involved with them,

00:58:01.030 --> 00:58:03.520
just as everything that
is temporary in life

00:58:03.520 --> 00:58:05.572
is not destroyed of meaning.

00:58:05.572 --> 00:58:06.780
This is from Buddhism, right?

00:58:09.524 --> 00:58:11.190
While things are
temporary, that doesn't

00:58:11.190 --> 00:58:12.250
mean that there's
not meaningful.

00:58:12.250 --> 00:58:14.208
In fact, that can actually
increase the meaning

00:58:14.208 --> 00:58:17.194
of those short times that
we have with those people.

